{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f5be58f9-8089-46e7-a0fb-c06fa822def2","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the CPU profiling profile:\n\n```bash\n# 1. Install the tool inside the container\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet tool` isn't available in the container, copy the tool from a sidecar or use `kubectl cp` to bring in `dotnet-trace`.\n- Add `--format speedscope` to get a JSON file you can open directly in Speedscope (no Windows needed).\n- For lower-level OS + runtime data, use **`dotnet-collect`** with `perf` or **`perfcollect`**, but `dotnet-trace` is the simplest starting point.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a27cd101-203b-47ce-b37f-e5046b5e0eda","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge/advisory question, not a code change task. I'll provide concise, practical guidance.","outputTokens":331,"requestId":"7843:15EDFA:395B4A:4279CF:69FA9954"},"id":"89ded657-4f3e-4969-af10-505719b26c10","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:29:00.824Z","parentId":"c3dc80df-2b52-4687-bf78-5b64b1049a40"}
